      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the joint",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pat the skin dry. Rub ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " firmly into the score lines and over the skin; it should feel like a salt crust. Drizzle ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " over the skin and rub in the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Leave the joint uncovered in the fridge for at least 2 hours, ideally overnight.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sage and onion stuffing",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a frying pan over medium heat. Add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{onion}} finely chopped onions",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and cook gently for 10 minutes until soft. Off the heat, stir in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sage}} of sage",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{breadcrumbs-fresh}} of fresh breadcrumbs",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Season well. Bind with the beaten egg. Tip into a small buttered baking dish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roast the joint",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 220°C (200°C fan). Roast the pork for 30 minutes to blister the crackling. Drop the temperature to 180°C (160°C fan) and continue for roughly 25 minutes per 500 g. The leg is done when the thickest point reads 75°C on a probe. Add the stuffing dish to the oven for the last 40 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and make gravy",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Transfer the joint to a warm board. Rest for 20 minutes. Pour off excess fat, leaving the fond. Add ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-chicken}} of chicken stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " to the pan, scrape well, and reduce for 5 minutes. Strain into a warm jug.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Ensure the skin is dry before seasoning. If the crackling is still tough after cooking, score it away from the joint and grill it on a foil-lined tray for 5 minutes.",
              "cause": "Skin was not dry enough, or the initial blast was not hot enough",
              "symptom": "Crackling is tough rather than crisp"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use a probe and pull the joint at 75°C. Serve with plenty of gravy and stuffing to compensate for slight dryness.",
              "cause": "Leg is a lean cut that dries out past 80°C",
              "symptom": "Meat is overcooked and dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Spread no more than 2-3 cm deep. Remove foil for the last 10 minutes to crisp the top.",
              "cause": "Too much egg, or not spread thinly enough in the dish",
              "symptom": "Stuffing is soggy in the middle"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pour juices into a tall jug, allow fat to rise to the surface (2-3 minutes), and spoon it off before making gravy.",
              "cause": "Pork leg releases more fat than expected",
              "symptom": "Pan juices are too fatty for a clean gravy"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roast leg of pork with sage and onion stuffing is the pork equivalent of the Sunday rib: formal enough for a gathering, straightforward enough for any confident cook. The crackling is the prize; the stuffing is the complement. Serve with roast potatoes, apple sauce, and a green vegetable.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
